    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1937-12-17T02:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1937-12-17T02:00:00-05:00" n="952"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d952">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">611.9431/140: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Japan</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Grew</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Tokyo</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1937-12-17T16:00:00+09:00"
                            >December 17, 1937—4 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received December 17—9:30 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>649. Department’s 351, December 16, 3 p.m.<note n="14" xml:id="d952fn14">Not
                        printed.</note>
                </p>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>We have, on several occasions when discussing at the Foreign Office
                        Japanese exchange control and regulation of imports and exports, <pb
                            facs="0815" n="807" xml:id="pg_807"/> pointed out that these measures
                        are not in harmony with American efforts to liberalize trade. We expressed
                        doubt whether there would be any basis for a trade agreement with the United
                        States so long as any tariff concession which Japan might make could be made
                        valueless by exchange and import control.</item>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>Yoshizawa,<note n="17" xml:id="d952fn17">Seijiro Yoshizawa, Director of
                            the American Affairs Bureau, Japanese Foreign Office.</note> with whom
                        these discussions were held, fully understands the position and in fact
                        indicated that the Japanese Government is not giving active consideration to
                        proposing a trade agreement with the United States. Nevertheless we will
                        take an early opportunity to clarify the situation.</item>
                </list>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Grew</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
